(^liberty^) already, and admitted of too much
delay, and we may not admit of any farther;
<P 71>
were it proper for us to do, we should hear
you freely, and we should not have declined
to have heard you at large, what you could
have said or proved on your behalf, whether
for totally excusing, or for in part excusing
those great and hainous charges that in whole
or in part are layd upon you. But Sir, I shall
trouble you no longer, your sins are of so large
a dimension, that if you do but seriously think
of them, they will drive you to a sad
(^consideration^) of it, and they may improve in you a
sad and serious (^repentance^) . And that the
(^Court^) doth heartily wish that you may be so
(^penitent^) for what you have done amiss, that
God may have mercy at least-wise upon your
(^better part^) . Truly Sir, for the other, it is our
(^parts^) and (^duties^) to do (^that^) that the Law
